---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Sales-Silva et al. (2026) - Chemical radial gradients in the bulge-bar - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Chemical radial gradients for the bulge-bar stellar populations from the APOGEE survey</h1>
        
        <div class="paper-meta">
            <p><strong>Authors:</strong> J. V. Sales-Silva et al.</p>
            <p><strong>arXiv ID:</strong> <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.12070" target="_blank">2603.12070</a></p>
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> 2026-03-12</p>
            <p><strong>Status:</strong> Accepted for ApJ</p>
        </div>

        <div class="abstract-box">
            <h3>Abstract</h3>
            <p>Using APOGEE DR17 abundances and chemo-kinematical segregation, the authors identify six bulge-bar populations and measure radial [X/H] gradients within R_gal &lt; 6 kpc, finding population-dependent gradient behaviour (see references)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-0">Key Findings</h2>

        <h3>Population Segregation</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>The sample separates into six chemo-kinematical populations: two bar-driven, two eccentric, and two low-eccentricity populations (each with low-/high-[Mg/Fe])<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Metallicity Gradients by Population</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Low-[Mg/Fe] low-eccentricity stars show slightly negative metallicity gradients; high-[Mg/Fe] low-eccentricity stars show slightly positive gradients — interpreted as a break in the global thin-disk gradient<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>High-eccentricity populations show approximately flat [Fe/H] gradients in the inner 6 kpc<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Element-specific Trends</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Most elements track Fe in their [X/H] gradients, except Ce and Nd which show different behaviour<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Bar / Peanut Structure</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>The high-[Mg/Fe] bar population exhibits a steep positive [X/H] gradient while the low-[Mg/Fe] bar stars are nearly flat; the authors suggest this traces an age variation along the peanut/boxy structure and cite agreement with N-body simulations and some high-z observations<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-1">Related Concepts</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/metallicity_gradients" text="Metallicity Gradients" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/bar_formation" text="Bar Formation" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/classical_bulges" text="Classical Bulges" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/APOGEE_survey" text="APOGEE survey" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/neutron_capture_elements" text="Neutron-capture elements (Ce, Nd)" /></li>
            <li><a href="/concepts/galaxy-bimodality">Galaxy bimodality</a> — bulge growth / secular evolution links to quenching pathways</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Implications</h2>
        <p>Inner Galaxy chemical structure is multi-component and population-dependent; using a single bulge metallicity gradient oversimplifies the chemodynamical complexity of the central regions<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>

        <h2 id="section-3">References</h2>
        <ol class="references">
            <li id="ref1">Sales-Silva, J. V., Cunha, K., Smith, V. V., et al. (2026). "Chemical radial gradients for the bulge-bar stellar populations from the APOGEE survey." <em>arXiv</em>:2603.12070. DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.3847/1538-4357/ae505e">10.3847/1538-4357/ae505e</a> (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.12070">arXiv:2603.12070</a>).</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galaxy_Chemistry" text="Galaxy Chemistry" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Bulge_Structure" text="Bulge Structure" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Spectroscopic_Surveys" text="Spectroscopic Surveys" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
